               <person xml:id="IDPe968">
                  <persName>Heinrich Ehinger</persName>
                  <note> (<persName>Enrrico Eynger</persName>) (†ca. 1537); member of the Ehinger
                     family of German merchants, linked primarily to the great banking and trade
                     enterprise of the Welsers, also cooperated with Italian merchants. Together
                     with other associates of the Welsers (Hieronymus Sailer, Albrecht Cuon, Georg
                     Ehinger), he dealt with overseas trade as well as the colonization of
                     Venezuela. Also involved in commerce were Heinrich’s brothers: Ulrich, Georg
                     and Johannsen, while Sebastian was a clergyman. Ulrich (d. 1537), like
                     Heinrich, was involved in commerce in Spain, and was a member of Emperor
                     Charles V’s council. Johannsen (d. 1546) was the Welsers’ factor in Memmingen
                     (NDB 4 Ehinger, p. 344-345). </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="IDPe156">
                  <persName>Hieronymus Sailer</persName>
                  <note> (<persName>Hieronymus Seiler</persName>) (1495 – 1559-06-15); in 1524 agent
                     of the Welsers' company in Spain, and later, from 1528, in Venezuela. After his
                     return to Europe, he dealt with the Welsers' affairs at the Spanish court, in
                     1540 he became their agent in Antwerp. Son-in-law of Bartholomäus Welser (;
                     POCIECHA 4, p. 260; NDB, Bd. 22, p. 355-356). </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="IDPe30">
                  <persName>Charles V of Habsburg</persName>
                  <note> (1500-02-24 – 1558-09-21), from 1506 ruler of the Burgundian territories
                     inherited from his father Philip of Habsburg (regency by his grandfather
                     Emperor Maximilian I untill 1515, abdicated 1556), from 1516 King of Spain
                     (abdicated 1556), 1519-1530 King of the Romans, 1519, Holy Roman Emperor of the
                     German Nation (elected 1519, crowned 1530, abdicated 1556); son of Philip I the
                     Handsome and Joanna the Mad of Castile. </note>
               </person>
               <person xml:id="IDPe437">
                  <persName>Hernán Cortés de Monroy e Pizarro</persName>
                  <note>(1485 – 1547-12-02); Spanish conquistador and Dantiscus' friend</note>
               </person>
